{"key":"processedPost-12437493","value":{"id":12437493,"first":12435104,"last":12934711,"when":1271959721,"utime":"04/22/10 09:08 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>jingus said:</strong><br />I pasteurized my bulk substrate in a 5 gallon bucket yesterday, with coir, vermiculite, and gypsum.&nbsp; &nbsp; but since there are almost 5 gallons of water in there, it all gets thrown out?&nbsp;  what do you guys have to say about this?</blockquote><br />By that reasoning, all the coir and vermiculite pours out too. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif\" alt=\":shrug:\" title=\":shrug:\"/> <br />However, you're FAR better off to hydrate the compost mix to the correct level and then pasteurize it in bags or jars.&nbsp; Don't pasteurize in water as if you were making soup.&nbsp; That's not how it's properly done, despite 'teks' to the contrary around here.<br />As for grains, I doubt any of the gypsum soaks into the interior of the grain.&nbsp; Most is captured in the porous surface of the grains where it helps prevent clumping, as well as to supply calcium and sulfur to the mycelium, both of which are essential minerals used in fruit formation.&nbsp; Some of it gets poured off when you drain the water of course, but using the amounts suggested leaves enough in place to work very well.<br />RR","title":"Re: Preparing rye"}}